<section xml:id="linear-systems-basics">
	<title>Linear System Basics</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			After exploring uncoupled, partially coupled, and fully coupled systems, we now turn to
			the most tractable and widely used class: <em>linear systems with constant coefficients</em>.
		</p>
		<p>
			Their algebraic form is simple enough for exact analysis, yet flexible enough to model
			everything from harmonic oscillators to interacting populations.  Our first task is to
			define what ‚Äúlinear‚Äù means and show how a short piece of matrix notation can replace a
			page-full of equations.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs xml:id="linear-definition">
		<title>What Makes a System Linear?</title>

		<p>
			A system is <em>linear</em> if every equation is linear with respect to its dependent variables (all to the power of one). For two variables
			<m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m> general form is
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = a x + b y</mrow>
			<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = c x + d y</mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m> are constants.  
			The system is therefore <em>autonomous</em> (no explicit <m>t</m>) and
			<em>planar</em> (two-dimensional).
		</p>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Select of linearity of each equation, then select the linearity of the system.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<areas>
				<p>
				<tabular>
					<row>
						<cell><me>\frac{dx}{dt}=</me></cell><cell><m>2x + 3y</m></cell><cell/><cell><area correct="yes">linear</area> ‚Äî <area correct="no">nonlinear</area></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><me>\frac{dy}{dt}=</me></cell><cell><m>xy</m></cell><cell/><cell><area correct="no">linear</area> ‚Äî <area correct="yes">nonlinear</area></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
				<tabular>
					<row>
						<cell>The system as a whole is:</cell><cell/><cell><area correct="no">linear</area> ‚Äî <area correct="yes">nonlinear</area></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</p>
			</areas>
		</exercise>

	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs xml:id="matrix-form">
		<title>The Matrix Formulation</title>

		<p>
			Writing the same system once more,
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = a x + b y</mrow>
			<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = c x + d y</mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			define the coefficient matrix and state vector
		</p>

		<me>
			A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix},
			\qquad
			Y = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix},
			\qquad
			\frac{dY}{dt} = \begin{bmatrix} \dfrac{dx}{dt} \\ \dfrac{dy}{dt} \end{bmatrix}
		</me>

		<p>
			Matrix multiplication then packages both equations into the single vector equation
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{dY}{dt} = AY.
		</me>

		<p>
			This compact format presents the system as a single equation, linking directly to linear algebra tools like eigenvalues, which we will explore later.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs xml:id="n-dim-linear">
		<title>From Two to <m>n</m> Dimensions</title>

		<p>
			For <m>n</m> variables <m>y_1,\dots,y_n</m> a constant-coefficient linear system reads
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{dY}{dt} = AY,
			\qquad
			Y = \begin{bmatrix} y_1 \\ \vdots \\ y_n \end{bmatrix},
			\quad
			A = \begin{bmatrix}
				a_{11} \amp a_{12} \amp \dots \amp a_{1n} \\
				\vdots \amp        \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\
				a_{n1} \amp a_{n2} \amp \dots \amp a_{nn}
			\end{bmatrix}.
		</me>

		<p>
			The dimension of the system equals the length of <m>Y</m>.  
			Our focus this chapter remains on the planar case (<m>n=2</m>) where geometry and
			algebra meet most clearly.
		</p>

		<p>
			The number of dependent variables is called the <em>dimension</em> of the system. For example, the three-dimensional system:
		</p>

		<exercise label="coeff-matrix-chkpt-1">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Give the coefficient matrix, <m>A</m>, for the following system: 
					<md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = 3x - 2y</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = z</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dz}{dt} \amp = 3x - y + 2z</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="10% 32% 3%" margins="27% 28%" valign="middle">
						<p><me>A=\left[\begin{array}{c}\\\\\\\\\\\end{array}\right.</me>		</p>
						<p>
							<tabular>
								<row>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="3" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="-2" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="0" /></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="0" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="0" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="1" /></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="3" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="-1" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="2" /></cell>
								</row>
							</tabular>	
						</p>
						<p><me>\left.\begin{array}{c}\\\\\\\\\\\end{array}\right]</me>		</p>
					</sidebyside>

					

				</p>
			</statement>
			
			<evaluation>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>3</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>\-\s*2</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>0</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>0</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>0</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>1</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>3</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>\-\s*1</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>2</strcmp></test></evaluate>
			</evaluation>
		</exercise>
	</paragraphs>

	<exercise label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-bundle">
		<title><e component="emoji">ü§îüí≠</e> Linear System Basics</title>

		<task label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-1">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Linear or Not?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Decide whether each system is linear or nonlinear.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = 2x + 3y,\\y' = -x + y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = xy, \\ y' = x - y^2\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
					<feedback><p>The product <m>xy</m> and the square <m>y^2</m> make this nonlinear.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = -4x + y, \\ y' = 5y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = e^x + y, \\ y' = -y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
					<feedback><p>The <m>e^x</m> term makes this nonlinear.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
		<task label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-2">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Identify Each System</title>
			<statement>
				<p>Select the linear systems.</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = 4x - y,\\ y' = 2x + 3y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = xy,\\ y' = x - y^2\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = -y,\\ y' = x\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = \sin x + y,\\ y' = x\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
		<task label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-3">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Benefits</title>
			<statement>
				<p>Choose all advantages of writing <m>\frac{dY}{dt} = AY</m>.</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>It condenses multiple equations into one.</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>It links the system to eigenvalues and eigenvectors.</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><p>It turns any nonlinear system into a linear one.</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><p>It eliminates the need for initial conditions.</p></statement>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
	</exercise>

</section>